<!--StartFragment-->

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">March 9,
2016<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">Dear
Everyone,<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">I’m writing
one letter to a lot of you as a bow to reality: I cannot keep up with
correspondence otherwise! I aspired until now to write you each individually to
thank you for your cards, thoughts, prayers, flowers, presents, and chocolate
(oh my, have we received chocolate!) but alas, it’s not going to happen that
way! I have never received more correspondence in my life, and while I spend
time on it every day, I get further behind each week.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">So here is
a glimpse of my current life since my sister Sonja’s death. My niece Pei and I
are living in the Cascadia co-housing community in Portland OR. Our unit is 900
sq. orderly feet, attached to the Common House, and with a tiny backyard
dominated right now by a blooming plum tree. About 35 people from 8 countries
live here. There are a couple of Common House meals a week and lots of
informal, spontaneous socializing, from tea parties to movies to impromptu
potlucks. The other day I was watching outside my kitchen window while my neighbors
practiced sword fighting on the bridge over the wetland. They are into some
obscure 15<sup>th</sup> century German martial art. Four-year-old neighbor
Akash comes over regularly to have me read to him – it’s a good time! I got a
library card and regularly walk to the neighborhood branch to get new books.
It’s fun to have an excuse to go back to old favorites!<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">Pei is a
senior in HS – a very hardworking and devoted student and very easy and
pleasant to live with. She has warm, close relationships with lots of Cascadian
adults, and we have one of them, Ken, over for dinner and games once a week. He
and Pei have been playing games together since she was four. Pei and I have
been steadily growing closer, and we have good talks fairly regularly. She is
tending actively to a growing social life, which is great to see – making new
friends, reaching out, and getting regular invitations. She has been accepted
into the honors program at Northeastern in Boston and hopes to study
engineering in the fall. She’s waiting to hear from more schools, but
Northeastern is high on the list.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">I’ve been
enjoying Cascadia a LOT. I’d have to go all the way back to my years in
Monteverde in the late 80’s to think of a similarly fulfilled time socially –
though our homeschooling years came close, marred mainly by the physical
distance that separated our families. It seems that only in an intentional
community do I find the depth and ease of connection that I really want. I’m
also attending two Friends Meetings on alternate weeks. The one Pei and Sonja
attended is one of them, the smaller offshoot with neighbors is the other. I’m
in a truly wonderful Bible study group that meets Monday mornings at 7 am for
granola and Luke – it usually takes us a full hour to plumb the richness of a
few verses. I love the “convergent” Friends that dominate the group – folks who
like the ecotone between conservative/evangelical and liberal/unprogrammed
Friends, which is my true spiritual home. I do miss our WI Friends worship
group, which is quieter and more intimate.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">This week
is the first time I have watched my to-do list actually get a little shorter.
It seemed for the first few weeks it just kept getting longer as new tasks were
added to it faster than I could check off old tasks. It was exhausting and
stressful and not what I’m good at! All those bills and legal things and stuff
about health insurance and life insurance and investments and lawyers and death
certificates and bank accounts and utility bills and people to notify… and
every task seemed to require some prior thing being done, which itself required
some prior thing… But I have learned that when I make a phone call to do
something like change the wifi service to my name, and they start asking me for
PIN numbers and other things I can’t provide, I can often get them to drop
their demands by just telling them what happened, and nitpicky paper pushers
become magically cooperative and attentive. My grace period for this sort of behavior
is probably running out, but I’m taking advantage of my excuse for incompetence
and ignorance as long as I can!<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">For weeks I
was stymied by my lack of a “letter testamentary” legally affirming my executor
role. This name seemed so perfectly Gilbert and Sullivan-ish that I have enjoyed
summarizing my frustrations poetically: <i>With
understanding rudimentary, tasks excrementary, no letter testamentary, Kat
became lachrimentary.</i> (Translation: confusion, shitwork, road block, puddle
of tears.)<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">One of my
weekly enjoyments is the Saturday morning “Cuss Yoga” class taught by Cascadia’s
resident forensic psychologist, Harry. He is intimately acquainted with the
darker side of the human psyche, and keeps up a running patter that is so
deliciously anti-PC I am tempted to record it. This is typical: </span><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;
background:white">"Okay everybody, settle into a seated pose. Choose
whatever accoutrements your twisted, mutant body needs to sit cross-legged.
Now... breath deeply... Relax.... Try not to think about Donald Trump... Be
mindful that in the moments you have been sitting here, another hair follicle
has probably died. Reflect quietly on your encroaching decrepitude. Roll your
head slowly clockwise, feeling the stretch. Limber necks, people, limber necks.
Later this morning we will do arm-free headstands. Notice the ripple of terror
that just went through your body. For some of you, bowels loosened.... Keep on
trying not to think of Donald Trump..."&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white">Another enjoyment is all the cultural
opportunities of living in a bigger city! I’ve been to movies, a women’s chorus
concert, an amazing theatrical performance of “Great Expectations,” and an HD
live broadcast from the Met of Puccini’s “Manon Lescaut.” Wow! I have been
given several gift cards to Powell’s, the largest independent bookseller in the
world, and wait in happy anticipation for the chance to use them! I also take a
lot of walks in the neighborhood. While the lack of sidewalks kind of sucks, and
the weather is not often lovely, I am enjoying all the blooming trees and
flowers, and the spectacular redwoods and sequoias of the nearby neighborhood. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white">While I have moments and hours where I am
suddenly ambushed by grief, most of the time I’m doing well. And the moments of
grief are not unwelcome either – just part of things. Sonja’s last year and a
half were so painful – she was suffering so much. I didn’t see an end in sight,
and the prospect of witnessing her pain in the long term without being able to
do anything about it was very hard. While I would never, ever have chosen this
outcome, there is in fact a lot to be thankful for. What came to me in worship
the other day was that Sonja’s suicide was like taking a rototiller to my
heart. It tore me to pieces, but already in the soil that was turned over good
new things are sprouting. Things that might not have sprouted without this. And
each day, with its ingredients both bidden and not, is another chance to make
something good. Most days ARE good!<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white">Pei and I receive daily demonstrations of
love from people – lots of meals (the soccer moms have been troopers!),
flowers, chocolate, invitations, offers of every kind of help you can imagine
(I have a whole spreadsheet on the fridge of Cascadia’s various forms of
expertise on offer), and opportunities to enter more deeply into friendships
with literally dozens of people. I have never felt more loved or supported, and
I think it’s fair to say that in her way Pei is blossoming. This is a huge
wound, and yet I see resilience and healing and growth, too.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white">My life is richer and happier than you
might imagine, and I’m seeing this time as a sabbatical and a time for renewal,
not just a time of mourning. I am quite content to be unemployed. (I told my
school district I wouldn’t be returning this year. I hear through the grapevine
that some things are messy in my absence, and I am losing exactly no sleep over
that. Sorry… and Not My Problem!) Thank you for the letters, cards, emails,
flowers, gifts, etc. that were pouring -- and are now trickling -- in. I’m sorry
I won’t manage to write and thank you all individually! All my love to you, <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white">Kat&nbsp;&nbsp;
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;background:white">Until mid-June: 4373 SW 94<sup>th</sup> St.
Portland OR 97225&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; landline:
503-644-1535</span><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>

<!--EndFragment--> 		 	   		  </div></body>
